Now I have all the context. Let me compile the full audit.

---

## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `SerializerTests.cs`

**Summary: 4 Critical · 2 High · 1 Medium · 1 Low**

This suite is dominated by **self-referential / tautological assertions** — tests that assert `output == input` using inputs carefully chosen (or accidentally chosen) so the operation is a no-op. They generate coverage but verify nothing.

---

### 🔴 CRITICAL — False confidence

**C1 · Self-referential assertion — `UpperCase_ToUpper_Works` (line 73‑77)**

Input `"HELLO"` is already uppercase, making `ToUpper()` a no-op. The assertion is always trivially true. Additionally, this tests `string.ToUpper()` — a BCL method — not any production code.

```csharp
// BEFORE — tautological
var input = "HELLO";
var result = input.ToUpper();
Assert.AreEqual(input, result);

// FIX — test a real transformation (and test YOUR code, not BCL)
var input = "hello";
var result = input.ToUpper();
Assert.AreEqual("HELLO", result);
```

---

**C2 · Self-referential assertion — `NormalizeName_AlreadyNormalized_NoChange` (line 37‑42)**

`NameNormalizer.Normalize` does `Trim().ToLowerInvariant()`. Input `"alice"` is already lowercase and trimmed, so the operation is a no-op. The test never proves that `Normalize` can actually transform anything.

```csharp
// BEFORE — pre-normalized input, nothing to verify
var name = "alice";
var result = NameNormalizer.Normalize(name);
Assert.AreEqual(name, result);

// FIX — supply input that requires transformation
var result = NameNormalizer.Normalize("  ALICE  ");
Assert.AreEqual("alice", result);
```

---

**C3 · Self-referential assertion — `GetDisplayName_ReturnsFormattedName` (line 57‑61)**

`GetDisplayName()` returns `Name` verbatim. The assertion `Assert.AreEqual(user.Name, display)` is structurally `AreEqual(x, x)`. The test name promises "FormattedName" but never asserts any formatting. If the method were ever changed to format (e.g., `"Alice (30)"`), this test would *fail* — proving it was never testing the right thing.

```csharp
// BEFORE — asserts field against itself
Assert.AreEqual(user.Name, display);

// FIX — assert against an independent expected value
var user = new UserDto { Name = "Alice", Age = 30 };
var display = user.GetDisplayName();
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", display);  // explicit expected value
```

---

**C4 · Self-referential round-trip hiding lossy mapping — `MapToDto_MapBack_RoundTrip` (line 46‑53)**

`Mapper.ToDto` drops `Id` and `Email`; `Mapper.ToEntity` drops `Age`. The round-trip is **lossy** — it cannot recover the original entity. The test structure (`entity → dto → entity → assert equals original`) can never verify that the forward mapping produced the correct DTO fields. Forward assertions are needed.

```csharp
// BEFORE — round-trip hides data loss
var dto = Mapper.ToDto(entity);
var backToEntity = Mapper.ToEntity(dto);
Assert.AreEqual(entity.Id, backToEntity.Id);       // 1 vs 0 — lossy!
Assert.AreEqual(entity.Email, backToEntity.Email); // "a@b.com" vs "" — lossy!

// FIX — test forward mapping directly
var entity = new UserEntity { Id = 1, FullName = "Alice Smith", Email = "a@b.com" };
var dto = Mapper.ToDto(entity);
Assert.AreEqual("Alice Smith", dto.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(0, dto.Age);  // document the intentional default
```

---

### 🟠 HIGH — Likely to cause pain

**H1 · Missing rejection-path test — `Validate_ValidInput_ReturnsSameInput` (line 64‑69)**

This is the **only** test for `Validator`. It asserts `input == result` for a valid email — which is trivially true since the method returns its argument unchanged. The entire throwing/validation branch is untested, so an empty method body would still pass.

```csharp
// ADD — test the rejection behavior
[TestMethod]
public void ValidateEmail_InvalidInput_Throws()
{
    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentException>(
        () => Validator.ValidateEmail("not-an-email"));
}
```

---

**H2 · Missing `AreNotSame` on clone — `Clone_ProducesEqualObject` (line 29‑34)**

The test verifies field equality but not reference independence. A `Clone()` implementation that returns `this` would pass all assertions.

```csharp
// ADD after the existing field-equality assertions
Assert.AreNotSame(original, clone);
```

---

### 🟡 MEDIUM

| # | Finding | Location | Fix |
|---|---------|----------|-----|
| M1 | **No negative/error tests** | Entire class | No test supplies `null`, empty string, or invalid data to any method. Add edge-case tests for `Money.Parse`, `NameNormalizer.Normalize(null)`, and `Serializer.FromJson<T>(malformed)`. |

---

### 🔵 LOW

| # | Finding | Location | Fix |
|---|---------|----------|-----|
| L1 | **Vague test name** | `UpperCase_ToUpper_Works` | "Works" conveys no expected outcome. Prefer `ToUpper_LowercaseInput_ReturnsUppercase`. |

---

